   "source": [
    "The main difference between a t-test and a z-test lies in the situations they are applied to:\n",
    "\n",
    "Z-Test: Used when you have a sufficiently large sample size (typically n ≥ 30) and you know the population standard deviation. It assumes a normal distribution. Example: Testing whether the mean weight of apples in a large orchard is significantly different from a known average weight (population standard deviation is known).\n",
    "\n",
    "T-Test: Used when you have a small sample size (typically n < 30) or you don't know the population standard deviation. It assumes a normal distribution and has heavier tails than the z-test. Example: Testing whether a new drug has a significant effect on blood pressure in a small clinical trial."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "4445291e-7ff3-4bff-8003-c6ce3eeb278a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "One-Tailed Test: In a one-tailed test, you are interested in the possibility of an effect in only one direction (e.g., greater than or less than). It focuses on one tail of the distribution. Example: Testing if a new treatment increases the average test scores of students.\n",
    "\n",
    "Two-Tailed Test: In a two-tailed test, you are interested in the possibility of an effect in either direction (greater than or less than). It examines both tails of the distribution. Example: Testing if a new manufacturing process affects the mean weight of products, without specifying whether it will be heavier or lighter."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "e1c4f473-d6a1-4b0e-a730-640ddebf9f66",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "Type 1 Error (False Positive): Occurs when you reject the null hypothesis when it is actually true. In other words, you conclude that there is an effect when there isn't. Example: Convicting an innocent person in a criminal trial.\n",
    "\n",
    "Type 2 Error (False Negative): Occurs when you fail to reject the null hypothesis when it is actually false. In other words, you conclude that there is no effect when there is. Example: Acquitting a guilty person in a criminal trial."
   ]
  },
