    " Bayes' Theorem can be used to update the probability of an event occurring given prior knowledge and new evidence. Let's say you want to find the probability of a patient having a certain disease (D) given a positive test result (T). The prior probabilities and conditional probabilities could be as follows:\n",
    "\n",
    "Prior probability of having the disease: \n",
    "�\n",
    "(\n",
    "�\n",
    ")\n",
    "=\n",
    "0.05\n",
    "P(D)=0.05 (5% of the population has the disease).\n",
    "Probability of a positive test result given having the disease: \n",
    "=\n",
    "0.90\n",
    "P(T∣D)=0.90 (the test is 90% accurate for true positives).\n",
    "Probability of a positive test result given not having the disease: \n",
    "=\n",
    "0.10\n",
    "P(T∣¬D)=0.10 (the test has a 10% false positive rate).\n",
    "Using Bayes' Theorem, you can calculate \n",
    "P(D∣T), the probability of having the disease given a positive test result."
